{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522406"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:44:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:44:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13827"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13827"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.49,0.06,0.35,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6444"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111838"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6444"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13827"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93908"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1387"},{"type":"tags","id":"2385"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9720"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12727"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12728"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42944"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44964"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45505"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111838"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with left ear pain and swelling three days after being hit on the ear. This was an accidental injury. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The left ear is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cellulitis","Perichondritis","Otitis externa","Auricular haematoma","Relapsing polychondritis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eperichondritis\u003C/strong\u003E. Perichondritis is an infection of the cartilage of the external ear, often occurring after trauma, ear piercing, or other injuries to the pinna. The presentation of erythema, swelling, and tenderness of the pinna is characteristic of perichondritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E of the ear would typically involve the entire ear and would not be limited to the cartilaginous portions. It also tends to have a more diffuse appearance and may extend beyond the ear itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOtitis externa\u003C/strong\u003E, or swimmer\u0027s ear, is an infection of the external auditory canal. While it can cause ear pain and swelling, the primary symptoms are typically located in the ear canal rather than the pinna itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eauricular haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when blood collects between the cartilage and perichondrium of the ear, often due to blunt trauma. While this is a possibility given the history of the ear being injured the presentation of erythema and tenderness two days after the injury is more suggestive of infection rather than a simple haematoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelapsing polychondritis\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune condition that causes recurrent inflammation of cartilaginous structures, including the ears. However, it typically affects both ears and is associated with other systemic symptoms, making it less likely in this acute, unilateral presentation following trauma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Perichondritis is an infection of the cartilage of the external ear, often following trauma or injury.","Perichondritis typically presents with erythema, swelling, and tenderness of the pinna."],"references":["Rivera-Morales MD, Rodr\u00edguez-Bel\u00e9n JL, Vera A, Ganti L. Perichondritis: Not All Ear Pain Is Otitis. Cureus. 2020 Oct 24;12(10):e11141. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7686808/","The Royal Victorian Eye and Ear Hospital. Perichondritis of the pinna. Clinical practice guideline: Emergency department. 2021. Available at: https://eyeandear.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Perichondritis-of-the-Pinna-Clinical-Practice-Guideline.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93908"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13827"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22051"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22051"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8KH4AD5lXOBZDdl7IBnsRJ06qMO6R6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8KH4AD5lXOBZDdl7IBnsRJ06qMO6R6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":1024}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93908"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-20T11:39:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-20T11:42:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6444"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111838"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position